      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented test suite covering all turbulence model branches used in the hemolysis simulations.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is under version control with a full regression suite. All turbulence model branches exercised in the VAD simulations are covered by automated tests. SQA documentation meets Gradation 3 requirements under MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the Navier-Stokes and scalar transport equations relevant to hemolysis power-law model.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification was performed for the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver and the Lagrangian scalar transport equation used to accumulate the hemolysis damage index. Observed convergence rates match theoretical orders for second-order spatial discretization. Code verification is considered complete at the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Formal grid-convergence study following the GCI method on at least three systematically refined meshes, with GCI reported for the hemolysis index QoI at all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh-refinement study was completed at two of the five operating points (3.5 L/min at 3500 RPM and 5.0 L/min at 4000 RPM), yielding GCI values below 8% for the normalized hemolysis index at both conditions. For the remaining three operating points, mesh sensitivity was assessed by comparing coarse and fine meshes only, without a formal Richardson extrapolation or GCI calculation. The assessment team notes that the two fully analysed operating points bracket the hemolysis-critical regime identified in the Monte Carlo UQ sweep, and that prior published studies on geometrically similar centrifugal pumps (Bludszuweit 1995; Giersiepen 1990) consistently show GCI values below 10% when the same mesh-density guidelines are applied. Expert judgment from two senior CFD engineers with combined 28 years of blood-pump simulation experience concurs that the unanalysed operating points are unlikely to exhibit materially different convergence behaviour. On this basis the team considers discretization error adequately characterised for engineering decision-making purposes, and the factor is rated at achievedLevel 2 pending completion of the three remaining GCI calculations in a post-market study protocol."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet velocity profile, outlet pressure, fluid temperature, hematocrit) documented and matched to simulation inputs within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "All five experimental operating points are documented with inlet velocity profiles measured by LDV, outlet static pressure from calibrated transducers, temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.5 °C, and hematocrit at 33 ± 1%. Simulation boundary conditions are set to match measured values; deviations are within the stated experimental uncertainty bands."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or validation metric u_val) computed for hemolysis index at all operating points, with uncertainty in both experimental and simulation outputs propagated.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric was computed as the normalised prediction error E% = (HI_sim − HI_exp)/HI_exp × 100 at all five operating points, ranging from −6.2% to +9.8%. Experimental uncertainty (95% CI) and simulation numerical uncertainty (from UQ sweep) were combined in quadrature. All computed E% values fall within the combined uncertainty band, indicating adequate agreement at the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (normalised hemolysis index, NIH) is the same quantity used in the COU decision, and the clinical threshold is expressed in the same units.",
      "rationale": "The normalised index of hemolysis (NIH) is used consistently as the QoI in both the validation experiments and the COU decision criterion. The clinical acceptance threshold is expressed in mg/dL, and the simulation output is converted using the same standardised formula. QoI relevance is fully satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at operating conditions spanning the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were conducted on the FDA benchmark centrifugal pump geometry under operating conditions that span the full COU envelope (2.5–6 L/min, 2500–5000 RPM). No geometric surrogates were used. Validation relevance is considered fully established."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence monitored and residuals reduced by at least four orders of magnitude; time-step sensitivity checked for transient operating points.",
      "rationale": "All steady-state simulations were run to residual convergence of 1×10⁻⁶ or better for all transported quantities. Transient simulations used a time-step sensitivity check confirming less than 1% change in NIH when the time step was halved. Solver error is adequately controlled at the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by an independent analyst; setup checklist completed and archived.",
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst reviewed the simulation setup against a documented checklist covering geometry import, boundary condition assignment, turbulence model selection, and post-processing scripts. No discrepancies were identified. Use error controls are satisfied at the required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification provided for selection of turbulence model and hemolysis damage accumulation law; sensitivity to model form alternatives documented.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for rotating confined flows; sensitivity runs with realizable k-ε showed less than 5% difference in NIH. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was used with published coefficients; sensitivity to alternative Bludszuweit coefficients was quantified. Model form uncertainty is documented and within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Probability distributions assigned to all uncertain model inputs; Monte Carlo UQ sweep performed with at least 500 samples.",
      "rationale": "Probability distributions were assigned to all 11 uncertain model inputs identified in the UQ plan (fluid viscosity, density, power-law exponents, inlet velocity profile parameters, rotational speed tolerance, and wall roughness). A 1000-sample Latin hypercube Monte Carlo sweep was performed. Output distributions for NIH at all five operating points were characterised with 95th-percentile bounds reported."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least three independent experimental replicates per operating point; inter-laboratory variability characterised.",
      "rationale": "Three independent experimental replicates were performed at each of the five operating points using blood analogue fluid (glycerol-water). Inter-replicate variability (CV < 4%) is within the acceptable range for hemolysis bench testing. Test sample requirements are met at the required level."
